Description: Estimates long-term cancer progression transition probabilities
    after local/regional recurrence (LR) using state-transition models calibrated
    to aggregate survival data from the Surveillance, Epidemiology, and End Results
    (SEER-17) registry. LR patients are modelled as transitioning to distant
    recurrence (DR) or death at constant monthly rates. Age- and sex-adjusted
    background mortality from US-CDC life-tables normalises relative survival
    estimates. Survival for LR and DR populations is extrapolated through
    standard parametric models (exponential, Weibull, Gompertz, log-logistic,
    log-normal, gamma); the top three AIC- or BIC-ranked distributions are
    blended using relative-likelihood weights. The mean LR sojourn time—the
    area differential between the modelled LR and DR survival curves—informs
    P(LR), while P(DR) is derived by approximating LR survival as the
    convolution of DR survival and LR-to-DR transitions. Sensitivity analyses
    cover BIC-based weighting and 5- and 20-year time horizons alongside the
    base-case lifetime horizon, spanning ten cancer types. The package provides
    a transparent, reproducible benchmark for calibrating cost-effectiveness
    models that incorporate an LR state.
